The product rule is an extension of the constant product rule, which you used to differentiate polynomials.


<ol>

<li>
<p>
<em>Constant product rule.</em>  Let <m>f(x)</m> be a differentiable function with derivative <m>\frac{ df }{ dx }</m>.  Let <m>g(x)=a f(x)</m> and <m>h(x)=f(x)b</m> for some constant numbers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>. Compute:
</p>
<p>

<m>\frac{ dg }{ dx } =</m> 
<answer>
<award>$d_af </award>
<award>$d_af_alt </award>
</answer>

</p>
<p>

<m>\frac{ dh }{ dx } =</m> 
<answer>
<award>$d_fb </award>
<award>$d_fb_alt </award>
</answer>
</p>


<hint>
<p>Since we don't know what the function <m>f(x)</m> is, the derivatives of <m>g(x)</m> and <m>h(x)</m> will be in terms of the derivative of <m>f</m>.</p>

<p>Online, enter the derivative <m>\frac{ df }{ dx }</m> as <c>df/dx</c> or <c>f'(x)</c>.</p>
</hint>

