<li>
<p>
<em>Product rule.</em>  If <m>f(x)</m> is a differentiable function with derivative <m>\frac{ df }{ dx }</m> and <m>g(x)</m> is a differentiable function with derivative <m>\frac{ dg }{ dx }</m>, what is the derivative of the product <m>h(x)=f(x)g(x)</m>?
</p>
<p>

<m>\frac{ dh }{ dx }=</m> 
<answer>

<award>$product_rule </award>
<award><math>f'(x) g(x) + f(x) g'(x)</math></award>
<award><math>df/dx g(x) + f(x) g'(x)</math></award>
<award><math>f'(x) g(x) + f(x) dg/dx</math></award>

</answer>
</p>


<hint>
<p>Since we don't know what the functions <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m> are, the derivative of <m>h(x)</m> will be in terms of the derivatives of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>.</p>
</hint>

